Abstract: We establish finitetime lastiterate guarantees for vanilla stochastic gradient descent in cocoercive games under noisy feedback. This is a broad class of games that is more general than strongly monotone games, allows for multiple Nash equilibria, and includes examples such as quadratic games with negative semidefinite interaction matrices and potential games with smooth concave potentials. Prior work in this setting has relied on relative noise models, where the noise vanishes as iterates approach equilibrium, an assumption that is often unrealistic in practice. We work instead under a substantially more general noise model in which the second moment of the noise is allowed to scale affinely with the squared norm of the iterates, an assumption natural in learning with unbounded action spaces. Under this model, we prove a lastiterate bound of order , the first such bound for cocoercive games under nonvanishing noise. We additionally establish almost sure convergence of the iterates to the set of Nash equilibria and derive timeaverage convergence guarantees.
